    "id": "04_KPPS_Reflection_Prompts",
    "filename": "04_KPPS_Reflection_Prompts.md",
    "title": "Student Reflection Prompts",
    "markdown": "# Student Reflection Prompts\n## Daily Practice Cards for Meta-Pet Learning\n\n**Print these as cards or use digitally**  \n**Students choose one prompt per session (or teacher assigns by focus area)**\n\n---\n\n## 🔵 Observation Prompts (Sessions 1–2)\n*Use these when learning to notice patterns*\n\n### Card 1: State Check\nMy Meta-Pet's mood right now is **___**.  \nThe vital that is lowest is **___**.  \nI predict this mood is happening because **___**.\n\n### Card 2: Cause + Effect\nI chose to **___**.  \nThe vital that changed was **___**.  \nThe mood became **___**.  \nOne thing I noticed: **___**.\n\n### Card 3: Four-Vital Scan\nToday I checked all four vitals in order:\n- Nutrition: **___** (colour)\n- Hydration: **___** (colour)\n- Rest: **___** (colour)\n- Stimulation: **___** (colour)\n\nThe mood was **___**.  \nThis tells me the system needs **___**.\n\n### Card 4: Pattern Spotting\nI've noticed that when my Meta-Pet feels **___**, it usually means **___** vital is low.  \nI tested this by **___**, and the result was **___**.\n\n---\n\n## 🟢 Wellbeing Prompts (Sessions 3–4)\n*Use these when connecting emotions to care*\n\n### Card 5: Mood Mirror\nMy Meta-Pet feels **___** today.  \nWhen I feel **___**, I usually need **___**.  \nI wonder if the Meta-Pet system works the same way.\n\n### Card 6: Recovery Practice\nMy Meta-Pet's mood dropped to **___**.  \nI helped it recover by **___**.  \nThe mood became **___**.  \nIf I need to recover from a hard day, I could try **___**.\n\n### Card 7: Care Sequence\nTo help my Meta-Pet feel **Calm**, I did these actions in this order:\n1. **___**\n2. **___**\n3. **___**\n\nThe order mattered because **___**.\n\n### Card 8: Resilience Reflection\nSomething didn't go as planned today (mood stayed low / vital didn't improve).  \nWhat I learned: **___**.  \nWhat I'll try differently next time: **___**.\n\n---\n\n## 🟡 Systems Thinking Prompts (Sessions 5–6)\n*Use these when learning STEM concepts*\n\n### Card 9: Homeostasis Check\nHomeostasis means a system staying balanced.  \nMy Meta-Pet's system is / isn't in homeostasis right now because **___**.  \nTo restore balance, I need to **___**.\n\n### Card 10: Input → System → Output\n**Input** (my action): **___**  \n**System** (what changed): **___**  \n**Output** (new mood): **___**  \nThis shows that systems respond to **___**.\n\n### Card 11: Feedback Loop\nI gave my Meta-Pet **___**.  \nThe mood became **___**.  \nThat mood is a **feedback signal** telling me **___**.  \nMy next action will be **___** because of that signal.\n\n### Card 12: Multi-Variable Thinking\nTo get my Meta-Pet to feel **___**, I had to work on **more than one** vital.  \nThe vitals I focused on were **___** and **___**.  \nThis shows that systems need **___**, not just one fix.\n\n---\n\n## 🟠 Data & Evidence Prompts (Session 6–7)\n*Use these when analysing patterns over time*\n\n### Card 13: Hypothesis Test\nMy hypothesis was: If I want my Meta-Pet to feel **___**, I need to focus on **___** vital.  \nI tested this by **___**.  \nMy hypothesis was **correct / incorrect** because **___**.\n\n### Card 14: Pattern Summary\nOver the past week, I've noticed that my Meta-Pet:\n- Feels **___** when **___** vital is high\n- Feels **___** when **___** vital is low\n- Responds best to **___** actions\n\nThis pattern tells me **___**.\n\n### Card 15: Genetic Variation\nMy Meta-Pet's system is **similar to / different from** my classmate's because **___**.  \nThis happens because each Meta-Pet has different **DNA**.  \nOne pattern that is the same across pets: **___**.  \nOne pattern that is unique to mine: **___**.\n\n### Card 16: Data Literacy\nIf I only observed my Meta-Pet once, I would think **___**.  \nBut after observing multiple times, I now know **___**.  \nThis shows why **data over time** is more reliable than one observation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔴 Metacognition Prompts (Session 7 + ongoing)\n*Use these when reflecting on your own learning*\n\n### Card 17: Systems Transfer\nI learned that systems need **balance** (homeostasis).  \nOne other system I know that works this way: **___** (e.g., ecosystems, my body, my classroom).  \nHow they're similar: **___**.\n\n### Card 18: Strategy Reflection\nOne strategy that works well for caring for my Meta-Pet: **___**.  \nI could use this same strategy in my life when **___**.  \nExample: **___**.\n\n### Card 19: Growth Recognition\nAt the start, I didn't understand **___**.  \nNow I understand **___**.  \nWhat helped me learn this: **___**.\n\n### Card 20: Future Application\nIf I keep using the Meta-Pet, I want to get better at **___**.  \nTo do that, I'll practice **___**.  \nI'll know I've improved when **___**.\n\n---\n\n## 🟣 KPPS Values Integration Prompts\n*Use these to connect Meta-Pet learning to school values*\n\n### Card 21: Respect\nI showed **Respect** today by:\n- Observing my Meta-Pet carefully before acting\n- Not button-mashing randomly\n- Treating the system thoughtfully\n\nOne way I can show Respect in my classroom: **___**.\n\n### Card 22: Resilience\nMy Meta-Pet's mood dropped to **___**.  \nInstead of giving up, I **___**.  \nThis shows **Resilience** because **___**.  \nI can use this same skill when **___**.\n\n### Card 23: Excellence (Personal Best)\nToday I tried to **___** (e.g., keep mood stable, restore balance efficiently).  \nI achieved / didn't achieve this goal.  \nWhat I'm proud of: **___**.  \nWhat I'll work on next: **___**.\n\n### Card 24: Cooperation\nI worked with **___** to observe our Meta-Pets.  \nSomething they noticed that I didn't: **___**.  \nSomething I noticed that helped them: **___**.  \nThis shows that **Cooperation** makes us smarter together.\n\n### Card 25: Community\nOne thing I learned about systems that I can share with my class: **___**.  \nOne question I still have that someone else might help me answer: **___**.\n\n---\n\n## Teacher Notes\n\n**How to use these prompts:**\n\n1. **Sessions 1–2:** Start with Observation Prompts (blue cards)\n2. **Sessions 3–4:** Shift to Wellbeing Prompts (green cards)\n3. **Sessions 5–6:** Use Systems Thinking Prompts (yellow cards) and Data & Evidence Prompts (orange cards)\n4. **Session 7:** Use Metacognition Prompts (red cards)\n5. **Ongoing:** Students choose prompts based on what they're working on, or teacher assigns by learning focus\n\n**Differentiation:**\n- **Simpler tasks:** Cards 1–8 (observation + wellbeing)\n- **STEM extension:** Cards 9–16 (systems + data)\n- **Advanced reflection:** Cards 17–25 (metacognition + values)\n\n**Student choice:**\n- Let students pick their own prompt to increase ownership\n- Or assign specific prompts to guide learning toward particular concepts\n\n**No \"correct\" answers:**\n- These are thinking prompts, not quizzes\n- Affirm observations and reasoning, even if conclusions are still forming\n\n---\n\n**Next document:** KPPS Values Integration Map (alignment tool for leadership)\n"
